orig_sentence:
Yatras have so much force and energy in them that even Mahatma Gandhi judiciously made use of them during his independence struggle and came out successful in uprooting the well grounded tentacles of British rule from India. The Britishers were so much in awe and fear of Gandhi's yatras that they never hesitated in arresting him and putting him behind bars. We have the resounding examples of Gandhi's "dandi march" and "non-cooperation movement" when Gandhi had contemplated so many yatras. Similarly in independent India's history we have the rare instances when we saw Lal Krishna Advaniji going on his famous rath yatras whereby he had succeeded in taking up the BJP's Lok Sabha seat tally from 2 to 83 and that instance had become a rallying point for the saffron party whereby it further improved it's prospects and established itself as a major national party for all times to come and holds on to that position right upto this day. 
Rahul Gandhi has also now dawned the mantle of the charismatic Gandhi in choosing to go on this "bharat jodo yatra". It is no ordinary feat and the BJP cannot take this yatra lightly or casually so as to ignore the impacts that this yatra is going to make on the mind and psyche of a brooding nation. For the first time in his political career has Rahul Gandhi undertaken a gargantuan and mammoth task of uprooting the might of Modi and if the charismatic senior Gandhi could succeed then in toppling the might of the British rule it would be no surprise to see Rahul Gandhi also similarly succeed in pushing the BJP to the brink of disaster and destruction through this "bharat jodo yatra". We wish him every success in this endeavour that is an opportunity of a lifetime that he has got, to do the unthinkable and prove once again the famous saying which goes on to say that "history repeats itself". Satyamev.

orig_sentence:
While Aurangazeb was passing near Varanasi on his way to Bengal, the Hindu rajas in his retinue requested that they halt for the day, so that their ranis could go to Varnasi, take a dip in the Ganges and pay their homage to Vishwanath.

Aurangazeb readily agreed and army pickets were posted on the five mile route to Varnasi. The ranis made the journey in palkis. They took their dip in the Ganges and went to the Vishwanath temple to pay homage. After offering puja, all the ranis returned, except one, the Maharani of Kutch. A thorough search was made of the temple precincts, but the Rani was nowhere to be found.. When Aurangazeb came to know about it, he was enraged. He sent his senior officers to search for the Rani.

Finally, they found that the statue of Ganesh which was fixed in the wall was a movable one. When they moved the statue, they discovered a flight of stairs that led to the basement. To their horror, they found the missing Rani there, dishonored and crying. The basement was just beneath Vishwanathâ€™s seat.

The rajas expressed their protests vociferously. As the crime was heinous, the rajas demanded exemplary action. Aurangazeb ordered that as the sacred precincts had been despoiled, idol of Vishwanath should be moved elsewhere, the temple be razed to the ground and the mahant be arrested and punished.

This evidence of history has been confirmed by the erstwhile curator of the Patna museum, Dr. PL Gupta.
